    "tagline": "The spinning egg of the Kuiper Belt",
    "overview": "Haumea is one of the strangest dwarf planets known, a fast-spinning, elongated world in the Kuiper Belt beyond Neptune. It completes a full rotation in under four hours, the fastest spin of any large body in the Solar System, which stretches it into an ellipsoid roughly twice as long as it is wide. Discovered around 2004 to 2005, Haumea is named for the Hawaiian goddess of fertility and childbirth. It has two moons, Hiiaka and Namaka, a bright crystalline-water-ice surface, and the distinction of being the first Kuiper Belt object found to possess a ring. Haumea anchors a unique collisional family of icy fragments scattered across the outer Solar System.",
    "sections": [
      {
        "heading": "A World Spun Into an Egg",
        "body": "Haumea rotates once every 3.9 hours, faster than any other known body larger than 100 kilometers across. This breakneck spin, likely imparted by an ancient collision, has deformed Haumea into a triaxial ellipsoid measuring roughly 2,100 kilometers along its longest axis but only about 1,100 kilometers along its shortest. The body is held together largely by its own rapid rotation and rock-rich interior; a less dense or more icy object would have flown apart. Because of this extreme shape, Haumea's brightness varies dramatically as it tumbles, a signature astronomers used to deduce its dimensions long before direct imaging. Despite the distortion, Haumea is still considered a dwarf planet because it would be rounded under hydrostatic equilibrium if it were not spinning so quickly."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Rings, Moons, and a Bright Surface",
        "body": "In 2017, astronomers watching Haumea pass in front of a distant star detected a narrow ring about 70 kilometers wide orbiting in the plane of its larger moon, making Haumea the first trans-Neptunian object known to be ringed. Its two moons, Hiiaka and Namaka, are named for daughters of the goddess Haumea and are thought to be collisional debris. Haumea's surface is unusually bright and covered in crystalline water ice, which is puzzling because radiation in the outer Solar System should convert crystalline ice to an amorphous form over time. This suggests the surface is geologically young or continually refreshed. A dark, reddish spot hints at a region richer in minerals or organic compounds, adding texture to an otherwise pale, icy world."
      },
      {
        "heading": "The Haumea Collisional Family",
        "body": "Haumea is the namesake of the only known collisional family in the Kuiper Belt. Scientists have identified a cluster of icy bodies sharing similar orbits and the same distinctive crystalline-water-ice spectral signature, all believed to be fragments blasted off a proto-Haumea by a massive ancient impact. That collision likely stripped away much of the body's icy mantle, leaving behind the dense, rock-rich, rapidly spinning core we see today, while flinging out the moons, the ring, and the family members. Studying this family offers a rare natural experiment, letting astronomers reconstruct a catastrophic event that occurred billions of years ago and probe the internal composition of a large Kuiper Belt object. Haumea's discovery was also marked by controversy over competing claims between teams in Spain and the United States."
      }
    ],
