    "tagline": "A reddish ice world of the far Kuiper Belt",
    "overview": "Makemake is the second-brightest object in the Kuiper Belt after Pluto and one of the largest dwarf planets in the Solar System. Discovered in 2005 by Mike Brown's team and nicknamed 'Easterbunny' because it was found shortly after Easter, it was formally named for the creator deity of the Rapa Nui people of Easter Island. Makemake is covered in frozen methane and ethane, giving it a distinctly reddish hue and a moderately reflective surface. For years it was thought to be moonless, until 2016 when the Hubble Space Telescope spotted a faint dark satellite. Lying around 45 astronomical units from the Sun, Makemake is a frigid relic of the early outer Solar System.",
    "sections": [
      {
        "heading": "A Methane-Frosted Surface",
        "body": "Makemake's surface is dominated by frozen methane, with ethane and possibly larger hydrocarbons also detected in its spectrum. The methane appears as large frozen grains, evidence of slow seasonal cycling as the world inches along its 305-year orbit. Sunlight gradually processes these ices into reddish tholins, lending Makemake a reddish-brown cast similar to Pluto but distinct from the gray-white of Eris. Its albedo of roughly 0.8 makes it quite reflective, though not as mirror-bright as Eris. When Makemake passed in front of a star in 2011, the sharp, abrupt dimming showed it lacks any substantial global atmosphere, in contrast to Pluto. If Makemake has any atmosphere at all, it must be extremely thin and possibly localized over patches where methane ice is sublimating under sunlight."
      },
      {
        "heading": "A Hidden Moon",
        "body": "For more than a decade after its discovery, Makemake appeared to have no companions, an oddity among large Kuiper Belt objects. That changed in April 2016 when the Hubble Space Telescope detected a small, dark moon provisionally designated S/2015 (136472) 1 and nicknamed MK2. The moon is roughly 160 kilometers across and orbits at a distance of about 21,000 kilometers, but it is around 1,300 times fainter than Makemake, which is why earlier searches missed it. Its charcoal-dark surface contrasts sharply with Makemake's bright icy face, possibly because the tiny moon's weak gravity cannot retain bright volatile ices, which escape to space. Studying MK2's orbit will let astronomers determine Makemake's mass and density with much greater precision, refining models of its internal structure."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Discovery and Naming",
        "body": "Makemake was discovered on March 31, 2005, by Mike Brown, Chad Trujillo, and David Rabinowitz, the same team that found Eris. Its discovery, along with Eris and Haumea, helped tip the scientific community toward redefining the term planet, since these sizable worlds clearly belonged to a populous new class. The team initially used the playful nickname Easterbunny because the find came just after Easter. When the time came for a formal name, the discoverers chose Makemake, the creator god and fertility deity of the Rapa Nui civilization of Easter Island, preserving the seasonal connection. Makemake was recognized as a dwarf planet by the IAU in 2008, becoming one of the original five officially designated dwarf planets alongside Pluto, Ceres, Eris, and Haumea."
      }
    ],
