    "slug": "vesta",
    "name": "Vesta",
    "category": "asteroid",
    "type": "Protoplanet (Asteroid)",
    "tagline": "The brightest asteroid and a battered protoplanet",
    "overview": "Vesta is the second-most-massive object in the asteroid belt and the brightest asteroid visible from Earth, occasionally faintly detectable with the naked eye. Discovered in 1807 by Heinrich Olbers, it is widely regarded as a surviving protoplanet, a building block left over from the era when the planets formed. Unlike most asteroids, Vesta differentiated into a metallic core, rocky mantle, and basaltic crust, much like the terrestrial planets. NASA's Dawn spacecraft orbited Vesta in 2011 and 2012, revealing a scarred world dominated by two enormous south-polar impact basins and confirming a long-suspected link between Vesta and a major class of meteorites that fall to Earth.",
    "sections": [
      {
        "heading": "A Differentiated Protoplanet",
        "body": "Vesta is not a typical rubble-pile asteroid but a coherent, layered body that came close to becoming a full planet. Early in its history it grew hot enough, partly from the decay of short-lived radioactive isotopes, to melt and separate into an iron-nickel core, a rocky olivine mantle, and a solidified basaltic crust. This differentiation makes Vesta a miniature analog of the rocky planets and a unique window into planetary formation. Dawn's measurements indicate a metallic core roughly 220 kilometers across. Had Jupiter's gravity not stirred the asteroid belt and stunted its growth, Vesta might have accreted into a true planet. Instead it was frozen in time as a protoplanet, preserving a record of the violent, fast-paced chemistry of the Solar System's first few million years."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Rheasilvia and the Giant Basins",
        "body": "Vesta's southern hemisphere is dominated by Rheasilvia, an immense impact basin about 500 kilometers across, nearly as wide as Vesta itself, with a central peak rising over 20 kilometers, among the tallest mountains in the Solar System. Beneath Rheasilvia lies an older, partly overlapping basin called Veneneia. The colossal collisions that carved these craters blasted roughly one percent of Vesta's volume into space and left a series of vast troughs wrapping around Vesta's equator, thought to be fractures from the shock. These two impacts ejected a swarm of fragments known as the Vestoids, smaller asteroids that share Vesta's orbit and spectral fingerprint, scattering Vesta's crust across the inner Solar System and eventually delivering pieces to Earth."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Meteorites From Vesta",
        "body": "One of Vesta's most remarkable legacies is the family of HED meteorites, named for howardites, eucrites, and diogenites. These basaltic rocks make up about five percent of all meteorites that fall to Earth, and their mineralogy matches Vesta's surface so precisely that scientists are confident they were chipped off the asteroid by the Rheasilvia and Veneneia impacts. This makes Vesta one of only a handful of Solar System bodies, alongside the Moon and Mars, from which we hold confirmed samples without a sample-return mission. Studying HED meteorites in laboratories, then comparing them to Dawn's orbital data, gave researchers an extraordinarily detailed picture of Vesta's geologic history. The asteroid thus serves as a natural cornerstone for understanding how early planetary crusts formed and evolved."
      }
    ],
