    "slug": "pallas",
    "name": "Pallas",
    "category": "asteroid",
    "type": "Asteroid",
    "tagline": "The tilted giant of the asteroid belt",
    "overview": "Pallas is the third-largest asteroid and one of the most massive objects in the asteroid belt, accounting for roughly seven percent of the belt's total mass. Discovered in 1802 by Heinrich Olbers, it was the second asteroid ever found and is named for Pallas Athena, the Greek goddess of wisdom. Pallas is notable for its remarkably steep orbital inclination of about 35 degrees, far more tilted than most asteroids, which makes it difficult to reach by spacecraft. Its battered, irregular surface and high tilt have earned it the nickname 'the most cratered object' of its size, and it has never been visited up close, leaving much about it still uncertain.",
    "sections": [
      {
        "heading": "A Steeply Tilted Orbit",
        "body": "What sets Pallas apart most dramatically is its orbit. While most asteroids circle the Sun within a few degrees of the ecliptic plane, Pallas is inclined by about 35 degrees, plunging far above and below the plane of the planets. Its orbit is also notably eccentric. This steep tilt means Pallas requires an enormous change in velocity to reach, making it one of the hardest large Solar System bodies for a spacecraft to rendezvous with, which is why it remains unvisited. The high inclination likely results from gravitational perturbations early in the belt's history. Because no probe has imaged it closely, our knowledge of Pallas comes from ground-based telescopes, the Hubble Space Telescope, and stellar occultations, which together sketch an irregular, lumpy shape rather than a smooth sphere."
      },
      {
        "heading": "A Heavily Battered World",
        "body": "Observations with the Very Large Telescope have revealed that Pallas is one of the most heavily cratered bodies of its size, its surface saturated with impact scars including two especially large basins. Researchers attribute this battering to Pallas' inclined orbit, which causes it to slice through the main asteroid belt at high relative speeds, leading to more violent and frequent collisions than asteroids on flatter orbits experience. The result is a pockmarked, golf-ball-like appearance. Pallas is classified as a B-type asteroid, indicating a primitive, carbon-rich, somewhat dark composition that may include hydrated minerals altered by water early in its history. Its overall density suggests a rocky body with significant water-ice content, hinting that Pallas could be a partially differentiated relic from the dawn of the Solar System."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Discovery and Classification",
        "body": "Pallas was discovered on March 28, 1802, by German astronomer and physician Heinrich Wilhelm Olbers, who also later found Vesta. It was the second asteroid identified, following Ceres just over a year earlier, and its discovery deepened the puzzle of why several small bodies, rather than one planet, occupied the gap between Mars and Jupiter. For a time Pallas was counted among the planets, before the swelling census of similar objects led to the asteroid classification. Today Pallas is recognized as the type body of the Pallas collisional family, a group of asteroids sharing similar orbits that are believed to be fragments from ancient impacts on Pallas. Despite being known for over two centuries, Pallas remains one of the least-explored large bodies in the inner Solar System."
      }
    ],
