    "slug": "bennu",
    "name": "Bennu",
    "category": "asteroid",
    "type": "Near-Earth Asteroid",
    "tagline": "A rubble-pile relic sampled and returned",
    "overview": "Bennu is a small, carbon-rich near-Earth asteroid and one of the most thoroughly studied bodies of its kind, thanks to NASA's OSIRIS-REx mission. Discovered in 1999, this roughly 490-meter-wide object is a loosely bound rubble pile, a heap of rock and boulders held together by weak gravity rather than solid cohesion. OSIRIS-REx orbited Bennu from 2018, briefly touched its surface in 2020 to grab a sample, and delivered that material to Earth in September 2023. Bennu is a primitive, ancient body preserving organic molecules and hydrated minerals from the early Solar System, and it is also a potentially hazardous asteroid with a small chance of striking Earth in the late 22nd century.",
    "sections": [
      {
        "heading": "A Spinning Top of Rubble",
        "body": "Bennu is a classic rubble-pile asteroid, an aggregation of rocks, boulders, and dust bound by mutual gravity with significant empty space inside. Its overall shape resembles a spinning top, with a pronounced equatorial bulge created as the asteroid's rotation gradually flung loose material toward the equator. OSIRIS-REx found Bennu far rockier than expected, its surface littered with large boulders rather than the smooth, sandy regolith mission planners had anticipated, which complicated the sampling effort. When the spacecraft's collection head touched down in 2020, it sank into the surface as if into a loosely packed ball pit, and the asteroid responded almost like a fluid, ejecting a plume of debris. This behavior revealed that Bennu's surface is extraordinarily weak and porous, with cohesion far lower than scientists had assumed."
      },
      {
        "heading": "The OSIRIS-REx Sample Return",
        "body": "NASA's OSIRIS-REx mission was designed to bring a pristine piece of Bennu back to Earth. After arriving in 2018 and meticulously mapping the asteroid, the spacecraft performed a brief touch-and-go maneuver in October 2020, firing nitrogen gas to blow surface material into its collector. It captured far more than the minimum goal, and on September 24, 2023, the sample capsule parachuted into the Utah desert carrying roughly 120 grams of Bennu. Initial analyses of the returned material found abundant carbon, hydrated clay minerals, and organic compounds, including amino acids and nucleobases, the chemical building blocks associated with life. These findings strengthen the hypothesis that carbon-rich asteroids like Bennu may have delivered water and organic ingredients to the early Earth, seeding the chemistry from which life later arose."
      },
      {
        "heading": "A Potentially Hazardous Asteroid",
        "body": "Bennu is classified as a potentially hazardous asteroid because its orbit brings it close to Earth's, and its size could cause regional devastation in an impact. Precise tracking by OSIRIS-REx sharpened the odds: there is a roughly 1 in 1,750 cumulative chance Bennu could strike Earth through the year 2300, with the most significant risk window around September 2182. While this probability is low, Bennu's well-characterized orbit makes it a key test case for planetary defense planning. The asteroid is also affected by the Yarkovsky effect, a tiny but persistent push from re-emitted solar heat that subtly alters its trajectory over centuries, a force scientists must account for to forecast its path. Bennu thus sits at the intersection of origins research and the practical science of protecting Earth from future impacts."
      }
    ],
