    "name": "Comet NEOWISE",
    "category": "comet",
    "type": "Long-Period Comet (C/2020 F3)",
    "tagline": "The dawn comet of 2020",
    "overview": "Comet NEOWISE, formally C/2020 F3, was the brightest comet visible from the Northern Hemisphere in decades and the standout naked-eye comet of 2020. Discovered in March 2020 by NASA's NEOWISE space telescope, it survived a close passage around the Sun in early July and emerged as a striking object in the dawn and dusk skies, sporting a long golden dust tail and a fainter blue ion tail. For several weeks it offered a rare spectacle to millions stuck at home during the pandemic, becoming one of the most photographed comets in history. NEOWISE will not return for approximately 6,800 years, making its appearance a genuine once-in-many-lifetimes event.",
    "sections": [
      {
        "heading": "Discovery by a Repurposed Telescope",
        "body": "Comet NEOWISE was discovered on March 27, 2020, not by a ground observer but by an orbiting infrared space telescope. The spacecraft began life as WISE, the Wide-field Infrared Survey Explorer, launched in 2009 to map the sky in infrared. After its primary mission ended, it was reactivated as NEOWISE to hunt for near-Earth asteroids and comets, lending its name to its most famous find. Infrared detection is well suited to spotting comets because their dust glows warmly, and NEOWISE picked up the comet while it was still inbound. The discovery gave astronomers a few months' warning before the comet rounded the Sun, allowing observatories and the public to prepare for what would become the best comet apparition for Northern Hemisphere skywatchers since Hale-Bopp in 1997."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Surviving Perihelion",
        "body": "Comet NEOWISE reached perihelion on July 3, 2020, passing about 0.29 astronomical units from the Sun, inside the orbit of Mercury. Many comets disintegrate during such close solar encounters as their ices violently vaporize, but NEOWISE held together, a sign of a reasonably robust nucleus roughly five kilometers across. Surviving the heat, it brightened dramatically and developed a prominent, broad dust tail that glowed golden from sunlight scattering off fine particles. A separate, fainter blue ion tail formed from gas ionized by ultraviolet light and swept back by the solar wind. Observers using telescopes and long-exposure photography also captured a striated structure in the dust tail and even hints of a sodium tail, echoing features seen in the great comets, all products of intense solar heating during the perihelion passage."
      },
      {
        "heading": "A Pandemic-Era Spectacle",
        "body": "For roughly three weeks in July 2020, Comet NEOWISE became a global phenomenon, visible to the naked eye low in the northwestern sky after sunset and, earlier in the month, before dawn. Its timing was poignant: with much of the world under pandemic lockdowns, the comet offered a shared natural wonder that people could safely enjoy from backyards and balconies, and it flooded social media with photographs set against landscapes, cities, and the aurora. It was the brightest comet seen from the Northern Hemisphere since Hale-Bopp. Calculations of its long, eccentric orbit show it originated in the distant Oort Cloud and will not return to the inner Solar System for about 6,800 years. For nearly everyone who saw it, NEOWISE was a strictly once-in-a-lifetime sight."
      }
    ],
