    "slug": "helix-nebula",
    "name": "Helix Nebula",
    "category": "nebula",
    "type": "Planetary Nebula",
    "tagline": "The 'Eye of God' cast off by a dying Sun-like star",
    "overview": "The Helix Nebula (NGC 7293) is one of the closest planetary nebulae to Earth, lying roughly 650 light-years away in the constellation Aquarius. Despite the name, planetary nebulae have nothing to do with planets; they are the glowing shells of gas shed by dying Sun-like stars in their final act before becoming white dwarfs. Often nicknamed the 'Eye of God' for its striking ringed, eye-like appearance, the Helix offers a preview of the fate awaiting our own Sun in roughly five billion years. Its expanding gas glows in vivid reds and blue-greens, energized by the hot stellar core left behind.",
    "sections": [
      {
        "heading": "Death of a Sun-like Star",
        "body": "The Helix Nebula formed when a star much like our Sun exhausted its nuclear fuel. In its final phase the star swelled into a red giant, then gently puffed off its outer layers over thousands of years. What remains at the centre is a tiny, intensely hot white dwarf, the exposed core of the former star, no larger than Earth yet blazing with ultraviolet radiation. That radiation lights up the expelled gas, making it fluoresce. The glowing shells we see are the star's former atmosphere drifting outward into space. This is precisely the fate that awaits the Sun in about five billion years, making the Helix a poignant mirror of our own future."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Structure and Cometary Knots",
        "body": "Though it looks like a simple ring, the Helix is actually a complex, roughly cylindrical structure of nested shells that we happen to view nearly down its axis, giving the illusion of an eye or doughnut. Its inner edge is fringed with thousands of 'cometary knots', dense clumps of gas each with a glowing head and a tail streaming away from the central star. Each knot is comparable in size to our solar system, and together they may contain as much mass as the Earth many times over. These knots form where the hot fast wind from the white dwarf plows into slower, denser gas ejected earlier, a turbulent boundary frozen in glowing detail."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Observation",
        "body": "The Helix Nebula was discovered before 1824 by German astronomer Karl Ludwig Harding. Because it is both nearby and physically large, it covers an area of sky about half the diameter of the full Moon, yet its light is spread thin, making it surprisingly faint and best appreciated in long-exposure photographs. Its proximity has made it a key target for studying the structure and chemistry of planetary nebulae in detail. Infrared observations have even hinted at a possible dusty debris disk around the central white dwarf, perhaps the battered survivors of a planetary system that endured the star's death throes."
      }
    ],
    "facts": [
      "It is one of the nearest planetary nebulae, only about 650 light-years away.",
      "Its nickname, the 'Eye of God', comes from its striking ringed, eye-like shape.",
      "The central white dwarf is roughly Earth-sized but far hotter than the Sun's surface.",
      "It is a preview of our own Sun's fate in about five billion years.",
      "Its inner rim is studded with thousands of comet-like knots, each as big as our solar system.",
      "It appears about half the width of the full Moon on the sky, yet is faint to the eye.",
      "'Planetary' is a misnomer, it has no connection to actual planets."
    ],
