    "tagline": "A city-sized stellar corpse spinning 30 times a second",
    "overview": "The Crab Pulsar (PSR B0531+21) is the rapidly spinning neutron star at the centre of the Crab Nebula, the collapsed core of a star whose supernova was witnessed in 1054 CE. About 6,500 light-years away in Taurus, this object packs more than the Sun's mass into a sphere only around 20 kilometres across, and rotates roughly 30 times every second. It sweeps beams of radiation across the cosmos like a lighthouse, pulsing from radio waves to gamma rays. Its discovery in 1968 helped cement the link between pulsars, neutron stars and supernovae, and it remains one of the most important objects in high-energy astrophysics.",
    "sections": [
      {
        "heading": "Birth from a Supernova",
        "body": "The Crab Pulsar is the dense remnant left behind when a massive star ended its life in the supernova of 1054, an event recorded by astronomers across Asia and the Middle East. When the star's core ran out of fuel, it collapsed under its own gravity, crushing protons and electrons together into neutrons and forming an incredibly dense neutron star. The outer layers rebounded and were blasted into space as the surrounding Crab Nebula. The pulsar's discovery in 1968, soon after the first pulsars were found, provided direct confirmation that these strange spinning objects are neutron stars born in supernova explosions, tying together several threads of twentieth-century astrophysics."
      },
      {
        "heading": "A Cosmic Lighthouse",
        "body": "The Crab Pulsar spins about 30 times per second, and with each rotation it sweeps two beams of radiation past the Earth, producing the regular pulses that give pulsars their name. These pulses span the entire electromagnetic spectrum, from radio waves through visible light to X-rays and gamma rays, making it one of very few pulsars detectable in optical light. The beams are generated by the star's phenomenally strong magnetic field channelling charged particles from its surface. Like all young pulsars, the Crab is gradually slowing down as it radiates away energy, and it occasionally undergoes sudden 'glitches', tiny abrupt speed-ups thought to reflect shifts in its superfluid interior."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Powering the Nebula",
        "body": "The Crab Pulsar is far more than a curiosity at the centre of its nebula; it is the engine that keeps the entire Crab Nebula glowing. As it spins down, it converts rotational energy into a relentless wind of high-energy particles and magnetic fields, pumping over 100,000 times the Sun's luminosity into its surroundings. This pulsar wind energizes the nebula's eerie blue synchrotron glow and drives shock waves and shifting wisps that astronomers can watch change over weeks. Without this continuous injection of energy, the supernova remnant would have faded long ago. The Crab is the archetypal 'pulsar wind nebula', a category of object defined largely by studying it."
      }
    ],
