    "slug": "psr-b1919-21",
    "name": "PSR B1919+21 (LGM-1)",
    "category": "pulsar",
    "type": "Radio Pulsar",
    "tagline": "The first pulsar ever discovered",
    "overview": "PSR B1919+21 is the very first pulsar ever discovered, detected in 1967 by graduate student Jocelyn Bell Burnell and her advisor Antony Hewish at Cambridge. Lying roughly 950 light-years away in the constellation Vulpecula, it emits radio pulses with astonishing regularity every 1.337 seconds. The signal was so precise and artificial-seeming that it was half-jokingly nicknamed 'LGM-1', for 'Little Green Men', before astronomers realized it came from a rapidly rotating neutron star. The discovery opened an entirely new field of astrophysics and is one of the most celebrated detections of the twentieth century.",
    "sections": [
      {
        "heading": "The Discovery",
        "body": "In late 1967, Jocelyn Bell Burnell was analysing data from a radio telescope she had helped build at Cambridge when she noticed a bit of 'scruff' on the chart recordings, a faint, repeating signal. Following it up, she found pulses arriving every 1.337 seconds with clocklike precision. So regular was the signal that the team briefly wondered if it might be artificial, even from an extraterrestrial civilization, prompting the playful label LGM-1, for 'Little Green Men'. When a second, similar source was found elsewhere in the sky, a natural origin became clear: these were a new class of cosmic object. The find was announced in early 1968 and stunned the astronomical world."
      },
      {
        "heading": "What It Really Is",
        "body": "PSR B1919+21 turned out to be a pulsar, a rapidly rotating neutron star, the ultra-dense collapsed core of a star that exploded as a supernova long ago. As it spins, it beams radio waves from its magnetic poles; each time a beam sweeps across Earth we register a pulse. The remarkable steadiness of the timing reflects the enormous rotational inertia of a Sun's worth of mass packed into a sphere only kilometres across. Far from being aliens, pulsars are among nature's most reliable clocks. PSR B1919+21 rotates once every 1.337 seconds, a leisurely pace compared with the millisecond pulsars later discovered, but groundbreaking as the first of its kind."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Legacy and a Nobel Controversy",
        "body": "The discovery of pulsars earned the 1974 Nobel Prize in Physics, but it was awarded to Antony Hewish and Martin Ryle, not to Jocelyn Bell Burnell, who had actually spotted the signal. The omission became one of the most discussed snubs in Nobel history. Bell Burnell handled it with notable grace and went on to a distinguished career, later donating a multimillion-pound 2018 Breakthrough Prize to support under-represented physics students. The pulsar's data also became unexpectedly famous in pop culture: a stacked plot of its pulses formed the iconic cover of Joy Division's 1979 album 'Unknown Pleasures', perhaps the most widely seen piece of astronomical data ever printed."
      }
    ],
