    "type": "Young Rotation-Powered Pulsar",
    "tagline": "A glitching young neutron star in the southern sky",
    "overview": "The Vela Pulsar (PSR B0833-45) is a young, rapidly spinning neutron star at the heart of the Vela supernova remnant, about 960 light-years away in the southern constellation Vela. Spinning roughly 11 times per second, it is one of the brightest pulsars at radio and gamma-ray wavelengths and the closest pulsar to Earth that is readily observable across many bands. Born from a supernova that exploded around 11,000 years ago, Vela is famous for its frequent 'glitches', sudden tiny jumps in its rotation rate that give astronomers a rare window into the bizarre superfluid physics inside neutron stars.",
    "sections": [
      {
        "heading": "A Young Remnant",
        "body": "The Vela Pulsar is the collapsed core of a massive star that exploded as a supernova roughly 11,000 to 12,000 years ago, an event that would have been a brilliant sight to Stone Age observers in the southern hemisphere. The blast scattered the star's outer layers into the surrounding Vela supernova remnant, a sprawling, tattered shell of glowing gas. At the centre, the crushed core survives as a neutron star spinning about 11 times every second. Its association with the supernova remnant, established in 1968, was among the earliest direct links proving that pulsars are neutron stars created in the violent deaths of massive stars, reinforcing the discovery made with the Crab."
      },
      {
        "heading": "The Glitch Laboratory",
        "body": "Vela is the archetypal 'glitching' pulsar. While pulsars normally slow down with extraordinary steadiness, Vela periodically undergoes glitches, abrupt, tiny increases in its spin rate, roughly every few years. These glitches are thought to occur when a superfluid reservoir of neutrons deep inside the star, rotating faster than the solid crust, suddenly transfers some of its angular momentum to the crust. By timing Vela's many recorded glitches, astronomers probe the otherwise inaccessible interior of a neutron star, testing theories about superfluidity, the stiffness of ultra-dense matter and how the crust and core couple together. Few objects offer such a direct, repeatable experiment on matter at nuclear densities."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Across the Spectrum",
        "body": "The Vela Pulsar shines brightly across an enormous range of energies. It is one of the strongest steady sources of gamma rays in the sky, studied intensively by space telescopes such as Fermi, and it pulses in radio waves, X-rays and even faint optical light. NASA's Chandra X-ray Observatory has imaged a striking jet and arcs of high-energy particles streaming from the pulsar into its surroundings, forming a compact pulsar wind nebula. These features twist and shift over months, captured in time-lapse X-ray movies. Its brightness, proximity and rich multi-wavelength behaviour make Vela one of the most thoroughly studied and scientifically valuable pulsars in the entire sky."
      }
    ],
